The Plate MethodIts easy to eat more food than you need without realizing it. The plate method is a simple, visual way to make sure you get enough non-starchy vegetables and lean protein, and limit the amount of higher-carb food that has the greatest potential to spike your blood sugar.Start with a 9-inch dinner plate:Fill half with non-starchy vegetables, such as salad, green beans, broccoli, cauliflower, cabbage, and carrots.Fill one quarter with a lean protein, such as chicken, turkey, beans, tofu, or eggs.Fill a quarter with a grain or starchy food, such as potatoes, rice, or pasta (or skip the starch altogether and double up on non-starchy veggies).

Diabetes Meal PlanningCounting carbs and the plate method are two common tools that can also help you plan meals.A meal plan is your guide for when, what, and how much to eat to get the nutrition you need while keeping your blood sugar levels in your target range. I doubt I can keep this short but I'll try. I have osteoarthritis, DDD and familial stenosis at L4/L5/S1 area. I've also have SI issues that has caused pain in my right foot for years. My left leg has had issues with going numb or the feeling of pins and needles in the same area from my big toe up to my knee. I had one spine specialist tell me that she didn't understand why I would have this issue if the pain is usually located on my right side. I had a SI injection in the area that caused the most pain. I have had off and on  tailbone pain for awhile also but it was never consistent. After the injection, I started having more pain in the lower back/tailbone area. It seems since then (October 2019), problems have been ramping up with both my legs as a whole. I'm not blaming the injection BTW (unless I should?). Now the pain is so bad in that area I can't even stand for a few minutes before the burning/stabbing feeling brings my pain level up to an 8.  I've been experiencing neuropathy pain in my knees that have been getting worse over the past week. Since this has been happening it's now occurring in my whole lower leg and the bottoms of my feet. I have to keep my legs stretched out in order to get any relief. When I get up to start walking, my lower legs will feel like pins and needles. When I sit back down that's when I start to feel it in my feet. Before all this I could feel pulsing in my knees after walking. Now I feel pain   Can this all be connected to my lower back issues? As the pain gets worse my mobility has gone down. I know this can make things worse in general. Thanks to anyone who took the time to read this :-)

Hi..I'm new here . Been reading everyone's post in neuropathy. I have type 2 diabetes and just got out of the hospital from a 2nd small stroke. Its been scary to say the least.i have neuropathy in both my feet and my hands as well.im now on plavix and Lipitor to monitor my levels. My a1c started at 12.8 back in October  and is now down to 9.5 but still needs to go down. I'm eating a Mediterranean diet and am watching everything that I eat. I'm doing whatever I can to get this to stop. But since I am home I have times where my arm or leg will get numb and I'm wondering if that is the neuropathy or the small stroke. I had the first one back in November so I'm always nervous and anxious. This last one I spent 6 days in the hospital being tested every day. Please offer any advice as to what will help with this.i dobt want this to take over me. Thank you all for listening!
